d Division around a Belfast Wall -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExploring the complex dynamics of twenty-first century spatial sociality, this volume provides a much-needed multi-dimensional perspective that undermines the dominant image of Northern Ireland as a conflict-ridden place. Despite touching on memories of “the Troubles” and continuing unionist-nationalist tensions, the volume refuses to consider people in the region as purely political beings, or to understand processes of placemaking solely through ethnic or national contestations and territoriality. Topics such as the significance of friendship, gender, and popular culture in spatial practices are considered, against the backdrop of the growing presence of migrants, refugees and diasporic groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGroup identityzNorthern Ireland. 0aPlace (Philosophy)xSocial aspectszNorthern Ireland. 0aSocial conflictzNorthern Ireland. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aBelfast.  aCultural Identity.  aIreland.  aNorthern Ireland.  aPost-Conflict.  aSocial Cohesion.  aUrban Studies.1 aBryan, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Young, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía González, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGazir, Augusto H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinson, Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomarova, Milena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomarova, Milena, eedit